oc:kn_020c11ac a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When establishing the design direction for any new interface" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Commit to a single BOLD aesthetic direction (brutalist, editorial, art deco, organic, luxury, etc.) and execute with precision. Bold maximalism and refined minimalism both work—the key is intentionality, not intensity. Every generation should vary between themes, fonts, and aesthetics—never converge on common choices." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Distinctive interfaces require a clear conceptual point-of-view. Timid, evenly-distributed choices produce forgettable results. Variation across generations prevents convergent AI aesthetics." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_07eb69c0 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PreFlightCheck ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before executing any design skill or generating any UI code" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Design context (target audience, use cases, brand personality) MUST be confirmed before any design work begins. Check loaded instructions, then .impeccable.md, then run teach-impeccable if neither source has context." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Without confirmed design context, all design output defaults to generic AI aesthetics regardless of skill quality. Code tells you what was built, not who it's for or what it should feel like." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_14c30737 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When defining color palettes, spacing systems, and responsive strategies" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use OKLCH for perceptually uniform color, tint all neutrals toward brand hue, never use pure black (#000) or pure white (#fff), use fluid spacing with clamp(), container queries for component responsiveness, and 4pt base spacing scale (4, 8, 12, 16, 24, 32, 48, 64, 96)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "OKLCH provides perceptually uniform steps. Tinted neutrals create subconscious brand cohesion. Pure black/white never appear in nature. Container queries enable component-level responsiveness independent of viewport." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_5d585642 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When making any visual design decision for frontend interfaces" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never use the AI slop fingerprints: cyan-on-dark palettes, purple-to-blue gradients, neon accents on dark backgrounds, glassmorphism everywhere, identical card grids with icon+heading+text, hero metric layouts (big number + small label + gradient), monospace for 'technical vibes', or rounded rectangles with generic drop shadows." ;
    oc:hasRationale "These patterns are the recognizable fingerprints of AI-generated work from 2024-2025. They make output look templated and generic rather than intentionally designed." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_7e973c70 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:RecoveryTactic ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When design context is missing and design work is requested" ;
    oc:directiveContent "If design context cannot be found in loaded instructions or .impeccable.md, immediately run teach-impeccable to gather context. Do NOT attempt to infer context from the codebase—code shows what was built, not who it's for or what it should feel like." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Inferring context from code produces generic output because code captures implementation details, not design intent. Only the human creator can provide authentic design context." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_8172d9bf a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When translating a chosen aesthetic direction into production code" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Match implementation complexity to aesthetic vision: maximalist designs need elaborate code with extensive effects; minimalist designs need restraint, precision, and careful attention to spacing/typography subtleties. Never use a cookie-cutter approach across different design directions." ;
    oc:hasRationale "A maximalist design with minimal code feels flat, while a minimalist design with complex code feels overwrought. Implementation must serve the aesthetic vision, not the other way around." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_b1aeed82 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "As a final quality check before delivering any generated interface" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Apply the AI Slop Test: if you showed this interface to someone and said 'AI made this,' would they believe you immediately? If yes, redesign. The goal is to make someone ask 'how was this made?' not 'which AI made this?'" ;
    oc:hasRationale "This self-check catches the subtle convergent patterns that emerge from AI generation and ensures output meets the standard of genuinely distinctive, intentional design." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_b2f80d38 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When implementing any CSS animation or transition" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Only animate transform and opacity—never layout properties (width, height, padding, margin). For height animations, use grid-template-rows transitions. Use exponential easing curves (ease-out-quart/quint/expo). Respect prefers-reduced-motion for ~35% of adults over 40 with vestibular disorders." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Animating layout properties causes expensive layout recalculation. Exponential easing mimics real physics. Ignoring reduced-motion preferences causes real physical discomfort for a significant user population." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_b56129ee a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When implementing interactive elements, forms, and user workflows" ;
    oc:directiveContent "For interactions: use progressive disclosure, design empty states that teach, use optimistic UI for low-stakes actions, provide visible focus rings with :focus-visible, ensure 44px minimum touch targets, use undo instead of confirmation dialogs, and test with real devices not just DevTools emulation." ;
    oc:hasRationale "These patterns address the most common interaction design failures: invisible affordances, poor error handling, accessibility violations, and the false security of confirmation dialogs." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_e1268176 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When selecting and implementing typography for any interface" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use distinctive fonts instead of overused defaults (Inter, Roboto, Arial, Open Sans). Pair fonts on multiple axes of contrast (serif+sans, geometric+humanist). Often one well-chosen font family in multiple weights creates cleaner hierarchy than two competing typefaces. Use fluid type for headings on marketing pages; fixed rem scales for app UIs." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Typography is the fastest way to establish visual identity. Overused fonts make designs feel generic. Contrasting pairings create visual hierarchy. Different interface types need different sizing strategies." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

